 BY NGOZI OKORIE THE Imo State Police Command, on Monday, arraigned 14 aides of former Governor Rochas Okorocha before the Magistrate Court 4, in Owerri. The aides were reportedly arraigned on a seven-count charge, bordering on disturbance of the security of the state and destruction of government seal at Royal Spring Palm Estate, Owerri. Their arraignment came just as the Police Public Relations Officer in the state, Orlando Ikeokwu, disclosed that Okorocha had been taken into custody to provide an explanation on why he led the action on Sunday. He said that the Command had received a distress call regarding what it termed to be an unrest at Royal Spring Palm Estate. According to him, the operatives, on getting to the place, found that Okorocha, who is the lawmaker representing Imo West Senatorial District in the National Assembly, had led some people to unseal the Estate. “The command received a distress call regarding what we termed to be an unrest at Royal Spring palm estate, and the operatives moved to the place, we discovered Okorocha led some persons to the place hitherto sealed by the Imo government,” he said. “The command calmed the situation and invited Okorocha, to come and explain why he led the violent breaking into the estate that led to damages,” Orlando added. The Police had arrested the former Governor, along with his then Deputy Chief of Staff (Domestics), Ijeoma Igboanusi; and Commissioner for Transportation, Lasbrey Okafor-Anyanwu, among others. 